SIMPLE: putrefy
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Putrefy
<hw>Pu"tre*fy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <altsp>[Written also
<ets>putrify</ets>.]</altsp> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Putrefied</conjf> <pr>(<?/)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Putrefying</conjf> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>putr⟦eacute⟧fier</ets>; L. <ets>putrere</ets> to be rotten +
<ets>-ficare</ets> (in. comp.) to make; cf. L. <ets>putrefacere</ets>.
See <er>Putrid</er>, and <er>-fy</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To render
putrid; to cause to decay offensively; to cause to be decomposed; to
cause to rot.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To corrupt; to make foul.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Private suits do <qex>putrefy</qex> the public good.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They would but stink, and <qex>putrefy</qex> the air.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To make morbid, carious, or gangrenous; <as>as, to
<ex>putrefy</ex> an ulcer or wound</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Putrefy</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Putrefy
<hw>Pu"tre*fy</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To become putrid; to decay
offensively; to rot.</def> <rj><au>Isa. 1. 6.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Putresce</ent>⟦br⟧
